## Content Schema

### Headset Markdown File Structure
Each headset should be a single markdown file with this frontmatter:

```yaml
---
# Basic Info
id: "arctis-nova-7"
name: "SteelSeries Arctis Nova 7"
brand: "SteelSeries"
price: 179.99
image: "https://ik.imagekit.io/yourproject/headsets/arctis-nova-7.jpg"

# Technical Specs (objective, filterable)
wireless: true
wired: true
connectivity: ["2.4GHz", "Bluetooth", "3.5mm"]
battery: 38 # hours, null if wired-only
weight: 315 # grams
driver_size: 40 # mm

# Compatibility (array of platforms)
compatibility: ["PC", "PS5", "PS4", "Switch", "Mobile"]
xbox_compatible: false

# Audio Specs
surround_sound: "7.1"
frequency_response: "20Hz - 20kHz"
impedance: 32 # ohms

# Microphone
microphone_type: "retractable" # options: boom, retractable, inline, none
microphone_detachable: true

# Features (booleans)
noise_cancellation: false
rgb_lighting: true
replaceable_earpads: true
sidetone: true

# Affiliate Links
amazon: "https://amzn.to/xyz123"
bestbuy: "https://bestbuy.com/affiliate/abc"
newegg: "https://newegg.com/partner/def"
manufacturer: "https://steelseries.com/gaming-headsets/arctis-nova-7"

# SEO
description: "Brief 1-2 sentence description for meta tags"
---

## Overview
Brief description of the headset (2-3 sentences max for SEO).

## Key Features
- List major features
- Keep concise
- Focus on objective facts

## Specifications
(Optional detailed specs section if needed for SEO)
```

## Feature Requirements

### Core Features (MVP)
1. **Main Listing Page**
   - Display all headsets in a grid/list
   - Client-side filtering by:
     - Price range (slider)
     - Brand (checkboxes)
     - Wireless/Wired (toggle)
     - Platform compatibility (checkboxes)
     - Battery life (min threshold)
     - Weight (max threshold)
   - Sorting options: Price (low/high), Battery life, Weight, Name

2. **Individual Headset Pages**
   - Clean layout with specs displayed clearly
   - Multiple affiliate link buttons (Amazon, Best Buy, etc.)
   - Price comparison widget showing all retailer options
   - Related/similar headsets section

3. **Favorites System**
   - Save/unsave headsets to favorites
   - Store in `localStorage` (no backend needed)
   - "Export Favorites" button → downloads JSON file
   - "Import Favorites" button → uploads JSON file to restore
   - Visual indicator on favorited headsets

4. **Export/Import Functionality**
   ```javascript
   // Export format
   {
     "favorites": [12, 45, 89, 103],
     "exportDate": "2026-01-12T10:30:00Z",
     "version": "1.0"
   }
   ```

### Nice-to-Have Features (Future)
- Share favorites via URL (base64 encoded IDs in query params)
- Compare 2-3 headsets side-by-side
- "Best for..." filtered views (FPS gaming, streaming, music, budget)
- Dark mode toggle

## Design Principles

### Filtering & Display
- **Focus on objective specs only** - no subjective reviews or ratings
- Minimize listicles - use prose and paragraphs for content
- Clear, scannable spec tables
- Visual indicators for key features (icons)
- Mobile-responsive filtering (drawer/modal on mobile)

### Content Tone
- Professional but approachable
- Fact-based, not opinion-based
- No hyperbolic marketing language
- Acknowledge when specs matter vs when they don't

### Performance
- All filtering happens client-side (fast, no server round-trips)
- Lazy load headset images
- Optimize images through ImageKit URL parameters
- Target Lighthouse score: 95+ on all metrics

## Data Management

### Adding New Headsets
1. Create new markdown file in `/src/content/headsets/`
2. Use AI to extract specs from manufacturer page (with manual verification)
3. Upload product image to ImageKit
4. Verify all affiliate links work
5. Commit and push (Netlify auto-deploys)

### Data Quality Rules
- **Always verify AI-extracted data** against official sources
- Cross-reference battery life claims with user reports (often inflated)
- Note when "7.1 surround" is virtual vs actual discrete drivers
- Check compatibility nuances (e.g., wireless on PC but wired-only on Xbox)
- Update prices monthly (can be scripted later)

### Data Sources Priority
1. Official manufacturer specifications
2. Official retailer listings (Amazon, Best Buy)
3. User reports on Reddit/forums (for real-world data like battery)
4. Tech review sites (for measurements, not opinions)

## Monetization Strategy

### Affiliate Programs
- **Amazon Associates** - 1-4% commission (priority: volume)
- **Best Buy Affiliate Program** - 1-2%
- **Newegg** - 2-5%
- **Direct brand programs** - Check Razer, Corsair, SteelSeries, etc.

### Link Presentation
- Multiple retailer buttons on each product page
- Price comparison showing current prices across retailers
- Clearly labeled "Buy on [Retailer]" buttons
- Disclaimer: "As an Amazon Associate, we earn from qualifying purchases"

### Realistic Expectations
- **First 3 months**: Expect $0-100 total
- **Months 3-6**: $50-300/month
- **Months 6-12**: $300-1,000/month (if done well)
- **Year 2+**: $2,000-5,000/month potential
- SEO takes 6-12 months to gain traction
- Don't quit the day job - this is a side project with long-term potential

## SEO Best Practices

### On-Page SEO
- Unique title and meta description for each headset page
- Use headset name + key features in H1
- Include specs in structured format (tables or definition lists)
- Alt text for all images: "[Brand] [Model] gaming headset"
- Internal linking between similar/competing headsets

### Content Strategy
- Focus on comparison keywords: "best wireless gaming headset under $100"
- Create category pages: "Best Headsets for PS5", "Best Budget Gaming Headsets"
- Write informational content: "Gaming Headset Buying Guide"
- Update content regularly (at least quarterly)

### Technical SEO
- Fast page loads (Astro is great for this)
- Mobile responsive design
- Clean URL structure: `/headsets/brand-model-name`
- XML sitemap (Astro generates automatically)
- Robots.txt properly configured

