## Code Style & Conventions

### JavaScript/TypeScript
- Use TypeScript where beneficial (Content Collections)
- Prefer functional components
- Keep client-side JS minimal
- Use descriptive variable names: `filteredHeadsets`, `priceRange`, `selectedBrands`

### Astro Specific
- Use `.astro` components for static content
- Keep interactive elements isolated to small components
- Leverage Content Collections for type safety
- Use Astro's built-in image optimization

### CSS/Tailwind
- Use Tailwind utilities primarily
- Extract common patterns into components, not custom CSS
- Keep responsive design mobile-first
- Avoid over-styling - clean and simple wins

### File Naming
- Kebab-case for files: `headset-card.astro`, `filter-bar.astro`
- PascalCase for components in imports: `<HeadsetCard />`
- Lowercase with hyphens for routes: `/headsets/steelseries-arctis-nova-7`

## Testing Strategy

### Pre-Launch Testing
- Test all filters with various combinations
- Verify favorites export/import works across browsers
- Check affiliate links redirect correctly
- Test on multiple devices (mobile, tablet, desktop)
- Verify all images load and are optimized
- Check page speed (Lighthouse audit)

### Post-Launch Monitoring
- Monitor affiliate link click-through rates
- Track which filters are most used (analytics)
- Check for 404s regularly
- Monitor page load times
- Review search console for SEO issues

## Constraints & Limitations

### What NOT to Include
- User reviews or ratings (subjective, moderation nightmare)
- Comment sections (spam, moderation)
- User accounts (adds complexity, costs)
- Real-time price tracking (requires backend/scraping)
- "Best" rankings or scores (subjective, like Versus.com complaints)

### Design Constraints
- **No bullet points in prose** - write in paragraphs naturally
- **Avoid listicles** - don't structure content as "Top 10 Best..."
- **Minimal headers** - use sparingly, keep conversational
- No excessive bold/emphasis in content

### Technical Constraints
- Keep site fully static (no server needed)
- No database (all data in markdown files)
- Client-side filtering only (no API calls)
- Images must be external (ImageKit, not in repo)

